"Photiadis G., Maries A., Tyrer M., Inman D., Bensted J., Simons S., Barnes P.","Low energy synthesis of cement compounds in molten salt",2011,"Advances in Applied Ceramics","110","3",,"137","141",,,10.1179/1743676110Y.0000000018,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79955071313&partnerID=40&md5=cb6844e5ffc865434641d02928cd1ee3","Centre for CO2 Technology, Department of Chemical Engineering, University College London, Torrington Place, London WC1E 7JE, United Kingdom; Department of Chemistry, University College London, 20 Gordon Street, London, WC1H 0AJ, United Kingdom","Photiadis, G., Centre for CO2 Technology, Department of Chemical Engineering, University College London, Torrington Place, London WC1E 7JE, United Kingdom; Maries, A., Centre for CO2 Technology, Department of Chemical Engineering, University College London, Torrington Place, London WC1E 7JE, United Kingdom; Tyrer, M., Centre for CO2 Technology, Department of Chemical Engineering, University College London, Torrington Place, London WC1E 7JE, United Kingdom; Inman, D., Centre for CO2 Technology, Department of Chemical Engineering, University College London, Torrington Place, London WC1E 7JE, United Kingdom; Bensted, J., Centre for CO2 Technology, Department of Chemical Engineering, University College London, Torrington Place, London WC1E 7JE, United Kingdom; Simons, S., Centre for CO2 Technology, Department of Chemical Engineering, University College London, Torrington Place, London WC1E 7JE, United Kingdom; Barnes, P., Department of Chemistry, University College London, 20 Gordon Street, London, WC1H 0AJ, United Kingdom","The world cement industry is responsible for .&gt; 5% of the total anthropogenic carbon dioxide emissions blamed for causing global warming. The production of cement clinker minerals by precipitation from a molten salt solvent offers a potential route to energy reduction in cement manufacture. Molten salt synthesis of the major cement compounds b-dicalcium silicate (β-Ca2SiO4, β-C2S) and tricalcium silicate (Ca3SiO5, C3S) has been attempted in fused sodium chloride (NaCl). The synthesis of b-Ca2SiO4 was carried out by the reaction of CaCO3 with SiO2 in molten NaCl (CaCO3-SiO2-NaCl mole ratios 2 : 1 : 19?2 at 908uC, and 2 : 1 : 20?4, 2 : 1 : 13?5, 2 : 1 : 10?3 and 2 : 1 : 8 at 1140°C). The product was characterised by powder X-ray diffraction, Raman scattering and scanning electronmicroscopy. For the synthesis of Ca 3SiO5, reactants with a molar ratio of 3 : 1 were used (CaCO3-SiO2-NaCl 3 : 1 : 19?8 at 908 and 1000uC, and 3: 1 : 20, 3 : 1 :14, 3:1:9?9 and 3 : 1 : 8?1 at 1140°C). In all cases β-Ca2SiO4 was the principal product, with the CaO phase still present and (if any) only small quantities of Ca3SiO 5. These observations, coupled with previous studies on the solid state synthesis of Ca3SiO5, indicate that β-Ca 2SiO4 is an intermediate compound, requiring in excess of 1140°C to react with CaO in order to form tricalcium silicate. © 2011 Institute of Materials.","Belite; Cement; Dicalcium silicate; Low energy; Molten salt; Synthesis","Belite; Dicalcium silicate; Low energies; Molten salt; Synthesis; Calcium; Carbon dioxide; Cements; Fused salts; Global warming; Precipitation (chemical); Silicates; Sodium chloride; Synthesis (chemical); X ray diffraction; Cement manufacture",,,,,,"(2010) Construction Statistics Annual, , http://www.corporatewatch.org.uk; (2010) US Geological Survey: 'Mineral Commodity Summaries, , http://minerals.usgs.gov/minerals/pubs/commodity/cement/mcs-2010-cemen. pdf; Hammond, G., Jones, C., (2008) Inventory of Carbon and Energy, , Version 1.6a, university of bath, bath, UK; Damtoft, J.S., Lukasik, J., Herfort, D., Sorrentino, D., Gartner, E.M., (2008) Cem. Concr. Res., 38, pp. 115-217; Gartner, E., (2006) Cem. Concr. Res., 34, pp. 1489-1498; Phair, J.W., (2006) Green Chem., 8, pp. 763-780; Winterton, N., (2005) Res. Intell. Newsl., (45), p. 7; Du, Y., Inman, D., (1995) J. Mater. Chem., 5, pp. 1927-1930; Tremillon, B., (1997) Reactions in Solution: An Applied Analytical Approach, 7, pp. 301-400. , (transl. D. Inman), Chapter, New York, Wiley & Sons; Du, Y., Inman, D., Morgan, H., (1996) Mater. World, 4, pp. 458-460; Al-Raihani, H., Durand, B., Chassagneux, F., Inman, D., (1996) J. Mater. Chem., 6, pp. 495-500; Du, Y., Inman, D., (1996) J. Mater. Sci. Lett., 15, pp. 1844-1846; Du, Y., Inman, D., (1997) J. Mater. Sci., 32, pp. 2373-2379; Du, Y., Inman, D., (1996) J Mater. Sci., 31, pp. 5505-5511; Inman, D., Legey, J.C.J., (1974) Physical Chemistry of Process Metallurgy: The Richardson Conference, 69. , (ed. J. H. E. Jeffes and R. J. Tait), London, IMM Publications; Chen, G.Z., Fray, D.J., Farthing, T.W., (2000) Nature, 407, pp. 361-364; Carthey, N.A., Kerridge, D.H., (1987) J. Chem. Soc. Dalton Trans., 10, pp. 2329-2331; Volkovich, V., Griffiths, T.R., Fray, D.J., Fields, M., Wilson, P.D., (1996) J. Chem. Soc. Faraday Trans., 92 (24), pp. 5059-5065; Aboujalil, A., Deloume, J., Chassagneux, F., Scharff, J., Durand, B., (1998) J. Mater. Chem., 8, pp. 1601-1606; Afanasiev, P., Geantet, C., Kerridge, D.H., (1995) J. Mater. Chem., 5 (2), pp. 347-352; Du, Y., Inman, D., (1996) J. Mater. Sci. Lett., 15 (21), pp. 1844-1846; Kanatzidis, M.G., Park, Y., (1989) J. Am. Chem. Soc., 111 (10), pp. 3767-3769; Palchik, O., Marking, G.M., Kanatzidis, M.G., (2005) Inorg. Chem., 44 (12), pp. 4151-4153; Clayhold, J.A., Ulutagay-Kartin, M., Hwu, S.-J., (2003) Inorg. Chem., 42 (7), pp. 2405-2409; Wang, Y., Lee, J.Y., (2004) J. Phys. Chem. B, 108 B (46), pp. 17832-17837; Xu, C.-Y., Zhen, L., Yang, R., Wang, Z.L., (2007) J. Am. Chem. Soc., 129 (50), pp. 15444-15445; Rørvik, P.M., Lyngdal, T., Sterli, R., Van Helvoort, A.T.J., Holmestad, R., Grande, T., Einarsrud, M.-A., (2008) Inorg. Chem., 47 (8), pp. 3173-3181; Geselbracht, M.J., Walton, R.I., Cowell, E.S., Millange, F., O'hare, D., (2002) Chem. Mater., 14 (10), pp. 4343-4349; Geselbracht, M.J., Noailles, L.D., Ngo, L.T., Pikul, J.H., Walton,